application_type_full: Outline planning permission: Some matters reserved
description: Demolition of four two storey blocks of flats providing 71 units of sheltered/elderly persons accommodation, and provision of four new blocks ranging from 2-3 storey to 3-4 storey, as part replacement and part on existing grassed areas, to provide a total of 123 homes for elderly and frail elderly, in four phases, with access from Fleming Road and Osbourne Road, car parking and landscaping (OUTLINE APPLICATION)
decision_conditions: Approval of details of the design, external appearance and landscaping, including surfacing (called the "reserved matters") shall be obtained from the Local Planning Authority in writing before any development is commenced.  Reason: The application is in outline form only and is not accompanied by full detailed plans, in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policies B1 and H26; Replacement UDP policies 4.1 and 5.5. | Plans and particulars of the reserved matters for each phase of the development referred to in condition 1 above, relating to the design, external appearance and landscaping of any building to be erected and the landscaping of the site, shall be submitted in writing to the Local Planning Authority and shall be carried out as approved.  Reason: To ensure that no part of the development commences until reserves matters are approved. This condition reflects the provisions of Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act and Article 4 of the Town and Country (General Development Procedure) Order 1995 in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policy B1 and H26; Replacement UDP policies 4.1 and 5.5. | Application for the approval of all the reserved matters shall be made to the Local Planning Authority before the expiration of three years from the date of this permission.  Reason: In order to comply with the provisions of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990. | The development shall be begun before the expiration of five years from the date of this permission or before the expiration of two years from the date of approval of the last of the reserved matters to be approved, whichever is the later.  Reason: In order to comply with the provisions of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990. | Notwithstanding the information contained in this application, nothing in this permission shall convey approval for the design, external appearance and landscaping shown in this application, and such details in relation to each phase shall be submitted in writing to the Local Planning Authority for approval and shall be carried out as approved.  Reason: So as not to fetter the Council's consideration of the detailed drawings in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policies B1 and H26; Replacement UDP policy 4.1 and 5.5. | Prior to the commencement of development hereby approved, the following detailed drawings in relation to each phase shall be submitted for approval to the Local Planning Authority and no development shall take place unless and until such details have been approved by the Local Planning authority. The details to be submitted for approval shall incorporate the following:   + Full plans, elevations and sections where appropriate of all buildings, screen walls, plant and/or machinery, structures and opening on external elevations to scale of not less than 1:100, incorporating details of all materials to be used for external surfaces including samples of all such materials;  + Full details showing the positions, height, design materials and type of boundary treatment.  + Full details of how sufficient light will reach habitable rooms of all accommodation, particularly north facing units.  + Details of external lighting  + Details of storage and collection of refuse, including full drawings at a scale of not less than 1:50;  + Details of cycle stands and shelters, including full drawings at a scale of not less than 1:50;  Any development shall be carried out and retained in accordance with the details approved by the Local Planning Authority.  Reason: In order to ensure that development achieves a quality external appearance and internal layout and is environmentally sound and compatible with surrounding development/land uses in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policies B1, B5, B26; Replacement UDP policies 4.1 and 5.5. | The access, pedestrian footways, parking, servicing and loading arrangements in relation to each phase hereby approved, shall be carried out for each phase of the development is first occupied or brought into use. Thereafter they shall be retained for such purposes and any changes to this layout will require the prior approval in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  Reason: To ensure that adequate access arrangements existing to serve the development in accordance with the Councils adopted UDP policy T63; Replacement UDP policy 9.11. | The turning /loading/unloading facilities approved in relation to each phase the development, shall accord with the current standards of the Local Planning Authority and shall be carried out for each phase of the development is first occupied or brought into use. Thereafter they shall be retained for such purpose.  Reason: To ensure that adequate facilities are provided and retained to service the development without creating conditions prejudicial to the free flow and safety of traffic on the adjacent highway network, in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policy B1; Replacement UDP policy 4.4. | All surfacing and landscaping approved in respect of each phase of the reserved matters shall be provided before the each phase of the development is occupied or brought into first use, or in accordance with a programme agreed with the Local Planning Authority. Any trees or plants which die or are removed within the first five years following the implementation of the landscaping scheme shall be replaced during the next planting season.  Reason: To ensure that the development is landscaped in the interests of the visual character and appearance of the area and assist in mitigating air pollution, in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policies B16 and ES4; Replacement UDP 4.5. | The refuse storage facilities approved in respect of each phase of the development, in compliance with condition 6, shall be installed before each phase of the development is first occupied or brought into use.  Reason: To ensure that adequate facilities for the storage and collection of refuse/waster re provided in a manner, which does not detract from the amenities of the neighbourhood, in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policy H34; Replacement UDP policy 5.5. | A construction strategy shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority prior to the commencement of any development hereby approved and thereafter implemented as approved. Such strategy shall address the following matters:-  + Limiting hours of potential noise nuisance. + Keeping nearby access free from obstruction and segregating construction and general traffic. + No burning of waste on site. + The suppression of dust. + The location of means of enclosure of sites for the storage of plant, materials and construction staff accommodation. + Means of securely enclosing construction sites. + Any temporary traffic control measures. + Temporary and permanent access to works. + Roads to be used by construction traffic and safeguards to prevent or limit damage. + The display of site notices informing residents of likely disruption including information on, and operating of, a complaints system. + Continuity of existing services. + Protection of the general public from health hazards. + Location and management of crushing, grinding and cutting operations. + Avoidance of blasting. + Public highway cleansing. + Sheeting of lorries during transportation of materials. + Controls to limit noise and vibration. + Details should be submitted to demonstrate recommendations for lighting of adverts and external lighting etc. will meet required standards. + Treatment of any asbestos in accordance with BS 6187 and Health and Safety Executive guidance Notices G8/29/1, 3,4 & 5 and other relevant statutory requirements and regulations. + Transportation and tipping in accordance with section 17 of the Control of Pollution Act and the Transport of Hazardous Waste regulations.  Reason: To ensure that any loss to residential amenity and general disruption are minimised during construction process related to the total development hereby approved in accordance with the Council's UDP policies B5 and B9; Replacement policy 4.11. | No more than 123 units shall be provided within the development: ultimately the ability to achieve this level of provision will be considered at the reserved matters stage.  Reason: To ensure that development contributes to the Borough's housing stock and regeneration of this part of the borough; and to ensure satisfactory living conditions for residents in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policies B5, H4 and H28; Replacement UDP policies 4.1, 5.2 and 5.5. | The total number of car parking spaces across the development hereby approved shall not exceed 28 spaces.  Reason: To accord with national and local policies to restrain the use of the car in favour of other more environmentally friendly modes of transport in accordance with deposit policy 9.8. | The developer shall comply with 'The aims and objectives of the Police requirements of Secured By Design'.  Reason: To ensure that the proposed development achieves the required crime prevention elements as detailed by the Government Circular 5/94 'Planning Out Crime' and with requirements of clause 17 of the Crime and disorder Act 1988 which imposes a duty on a Local Authority 'to do all that it can to prevent crime and disorder in its area' in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policy B20; Replacement policy 4.1. | Before any works commence on the site in respect of each phase of the development, details of a pedestrian access scheme within the site, in accordance with the Council's standards, shall be submitted to and approved by the local Planning Authority. Development shall be carried out in accordance with approved details before first occupation of the relevant phase of the development and thereafter permanently be retained.  To provide adequate facilities for pedestrians and in the interests of sustainable Development in accordance with the council's adopted UDP policies T12; Replacement UDP policy 9.9. | Details of access for people with disabilities in relation to each phase shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority before any work is commenced; and the approved scheme shall be implemented for each phase before the first occupation of residential accommodation, and shall be permanently retained.   Reason: To ensure adequate provision for people with disabilities, in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policies B1, B6, ES3, H12; Replacement UDP policies 4.1, 4.3 and 5.3. | The heights of the development hereby approved shall not exceed 13.5m to the ridge and 10m to eaves for the four storey elements and 11m to the ridge and 7.3m to eaves for the three storey element.  Reason: To ensure a satisfactory form and scale of development, in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policy b1 and B5; replacement UDP policies 4.1 and 5.5. | The car parking spaces on the approved site plan A1582/2.1/01 dated 07/10/03 shall be marked out on site prior to first occupation of each phase of the development, and these spaces shall be kept continuously available for car parking and shall not be used for any other purpose.   Reason: To ensure that there is adequate provision of car parking within the site, in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policy T51; Replacement UDP 9.1. | Details requiring the submission of a detailed Green Travel Plan, designed to manage the transport needs of staff to minimise car usage and promote alternative modes of transport, reduce on site parking, shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of any work on site, The approved scheme shall be implemented at the time of first occupation of any part of the development and shall be permanently retained in operation thereafter.  Reason:  To ensure that the Council's policies on sustainability are met, in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policies T1 & T40; Replacement UDP policies 9.1 & 9.11. | Prior to the commencement of any development full details in relation to each phase of pedestrian visibility splays at locations where pedestrian and vehicle movements conflict shall be submitted to the local planning authority for approval and brought into use before the development hereby approved is first occupied, and retained thereafter.  Reason: In the interests of highway and pedestrian safety, in accordance with the Council's adopted UDP policy T63; Replacement UDP policy 9.9.
